</P>
<P>
   That mind, by all accounts and evidence, is a staggeringly
active one, stoked constantly by the thousands of thick volumes of
prose (almost all of it nonfiction) that he owns. These books are
carefully organized in his home study: political philosophy in one
section, the musings of Thomas Jefferson in another, the collected
works of Winston Churchill nearby. The walls around them are
adorned with vintage photographs and portraits of American
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Rove is so interested in history that he literally lives in it,
although that was not easy to arrange: He and his second wife,
Darby, a graphic artist, found the late 19th-century Texas
farmhouse of their dreams on a rural road far from Austin and had
it split into three pieces so that it could be moved 100 miles and
reassembled on a hill outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   Rove, 49, grew up in various states along the Rocky Mountains,
where his father's career as a geologist took the family. He
attended the University of Utah and George Mason University in
Virginia, but never received a college degree; he said he was too
distracted by, and preoccupied with, the political work he was
doing on the side.
</P>
<P>
   One summer, in an early indication of his killer instincts, Rove
got hold of some stationery with a Democratic candidate's
letterhead on it, forged an invitation promising ``free food, girls
and a good time'' at the candidate's headquarters and distributed
hundreds of the invitations to poor and homeless people.
</P>
<P>
   Rove said that such mischief is behind him, but some political
peers said that a ruthless competitive spirit is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who gets in the way of his ambitions for the governor
gets run off,'' said Tom Pauken, a former chairman of the
Republican Party in Texas. ``And if you're not with Karl 100
percent, you're an enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald put it more diplomatically. ``Karl plays as fair as
anybody else in politics,'' he said, ``but he plays for keeps. I
always knew where I stood with Karl. I knew he was trying to kill
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rove's peers say that he is a master at creating a sense of
momentum, and they credit him with orchestrating the thick parade
of Republican luminaries to the governor's mansion in Austin and
the seemingly endless rollout of endorsements while Bush stayed off
the campaign trail last winter and spring, creating a keen sense of
anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, some of it was Bush's salesmanship,'' said Charles
Black, a Republican strategist in Washington. But, Black said,
``Karl's ability to use Austin as a base and organize the country
from there was amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rove has overseen the Bush campaign's effort in every
early-primary state to identify _ by phone, home visits and other
means _ potential supporters of Bush, and to try to ascertain that
Bush has the necessary votes to win.
</P>
<P>
   That is a vestige of Rove's extensive, earlier work in
direct-mail consulting. It is also where a good chunk of Bush's
financial war chest has gone, and it could ultimately prove more
critical to victory than the dazzling aspects of campaigning that
attract public notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karl's a meticulous planner,'' said Stuart Stevens, one of the
Bush campaign's principal media advisers. Stevens remembered
watching Rove, in a coffeehouse in Austin in April, map out the
Bush effort for the rest of the year on the only kind of paper
within reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five napkins later, you had the structure of an entire
presidential campaign,'' Stevens said. ``Then Karl just left. I
went back to get the napkins.''
</P>
<P>
   Rove has put boundless energy and thought into Bush's political
ascent _ at Rove's consulting firm there was always a special, red
phone for Bush's incoming calls _ and he has sacrificed for it.
</P>
<P>
   He once had a lucrative consulting contract with the tobacco
industry, but he gave it up when it became an embarrassing
political situation for the Texas governor. He was once his own
boss, with his own eponymous business, but no more.
</P>
<P>
   And after a few episodes in which he seemed to upstage and upset
Bush, he learned to bury his ego, to belittle his own
contributions. Much as Ms. Hughes kept her name off the cover of
the autobiography of Bush that she wrote, Rove spent considerable
time during interviews deferring to Bush as the real political
genius, the leader whose insights are the most vital, whose
interests can never be promoted too zealously.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my friend,'' Rove said. ``He's my friend, and I love
him.''
</P>
